TY  - JOUR
T1  - Poker Player Behavior After Big Wins and Big Losses
AU  - Smith, Gary
AU  - Levere, Michael
AU  - Kurtzman, Robert
Y1  - 2009/07/10
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1090.1044
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1090.1044
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1547
EP  - 1555
VL  - 55
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We find that experienced poker players typically change their style of play after winning or losing a big pot?most notably, playing less cautiously after a big loss, evidently hoping for lucky cards that will erase their loss. This finding is consistent with Kahneman and Tversky's (Kahneman, D., A. Tversky. 1979. Prospect theory: An analysis of decision under risk. Econometrica 47(2) 263?292) break-even hypothesis and suggests that when investors incur a large loss, it might be time to take a vacation or be monitored closely.
AB  - We find that experienced poker players typically change their style of play after winning or losing a big pot?most notably, playing less cautiously after a big loss, evidently hoping for lucky cards that will erase their loss. This finding is consistent with Kahneman and Tversky's (Kahneman, D., A. Tversky. 1979. Prospect theory: An analysis of decision under risk. Econometrica 47(2) 263?292) break-even hypothesis and suggests that when investors incur a large loss, it might be time to take a vacation or be monitored closely.
